e because you can't capture span parameters that way. resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, and since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it can't be used in expression trees. The workaround is to either call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first. Though the user mentioned a runtime error specifically, this would typically be a compile-time issue, but either way the fix is the same.\n\nActually, wait—what if the compiler in C# 14 is emitting the expression tree with the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload without flagging it as an error, and then the expression tree interpreter fails at runtime when it tries to handle the ref struct parameter? That would explain why it throws at runtime rather than compile time. The compiler might not have caught up to reject the new span-based overloads in expression trees, so the `Expression.Call` node references the incompatible method, and the interpreter chokes when trying to execute it.\n\nI think that's the right explanation. The compiler lets it through—possibly because the ref struct check wasn't updated for implicit span conversions—but the runtime interpreter can't handle the ref struct conversion, so it fails when you actually try to compile and run the expression tree.\n\nThis is actually a known breaking change in .NET 10 and C# 14: the implicit span conversions cause `array.Contains(x)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, which breaks expression trees since ref structs aren't allowed in them. It also subtly changes behavior in other ways.\n\nI'm ready to write this up.","outputTokens":4535,"requestId":"CFC0:929D2:11427D:14B301:69E81965"},"id":"f4599f1d-cdf0-4412-8be1-c03ab021a77c","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:43:45.111Z","parentId":"bee4547f-d3a8-4b13-8a3b-f35f302c33a4"}
